# Workflow Error Handling Conventions

All failures raise exceptions. The `success` and `error` fields in the run webhook are provided by the framework automatically — they are **not** fields you define in `Result`.

## The Rule

| Condition | Pattern |
|-----------|---------|
| Any failure — browser won't open, login rejected, item not found, extraction empty | `raise RuntimeError("...")` or `raise ValueError("...")` |
| Recoverable failure (can retry or take an alternative path) | `try/except` then retry or fallback, re-raise if unrecoverable |

## ✅ Raise for all failures

```python
# Browser won't open
if not agent.verify("Is the Chromium browser open?", timeout=10):
    raise RuntimeError("Failed to open Chromium browser")

# Site is unreachable
if not agent.verify("Is the page loaded?", timeout=20):
    raise RuntimeError(f"Failed to load {params.url}")

# Login failed
if agent.verify("Are we still on the login page?", timeout=10):
    raise RuntimeError("Login failed — still on login page after submitting credentials")

# Extraction returned nothing useful
data = agent.extract("Extract the order ID", Result.model_json_schema())
if not data.get("order_id"):
    raise ValueError("No order ID found on the page")
```

## ✅ Catch only for recovery (retry or alternative path)

```python
# Retry pattern
for attempt in range(3):
    try:
        agent.execute("Click Submit")
        break
    except WorkflowError:
        if attempt == 2:
            raise
        agent.execute("Scroll down to find the Submit button")

# Alternative path
try:
    agent.execute("Click the Export button")
except WorkflowError:
    agent.execute("Open the File menu and click Export")
```

## ❌ Wrong — returning Result with success/error fields

```python
# DO NOT define success or error in Result
class Result(BaseModel):
    success: bool        # ❌ framework-provided
    error: str | None    # ❌ framework-provided

# DO NOT return Result(success=False, ...)
if not agent.verify("Is the page loaded?"):
    return Result(success=False, error="Failed to load page")  # ❌

# DO NOT return Result(success=True) — omit success from Result entirely
return Result(success=True)  # ❌
```

## ✅ Correct — Result contains only output data

```python
class Result(BaseModel):
    customer_id: str
    account_name: str

def run(params: Params) -> Result:
    agent = Agent()

    if not agent.verify("Is the dashboard loaded?", timeout=20):
        raise RuntimeError("Dashboard did not load")  # ✅

    data = agent.extract("Extract customer info", Result.model_json_schema())
    return Result.model_construct(**data)  # ✅
```

## Key Principle

> Raise for all failures. Catch only when you can meaningfully recover. `success` and `error` in the webhook payload are automatically set by the framework — any uncaught exception becomes `{"success": false, "error": "..."}`.
